{{for|the human practice of affection|Touching heads}} '''Head pressing''' is a [[veterinary]] condition characterized by standing close to a wall or corner face-first without moving.{{clarification needed|date=September 2015}} This condition is seen in pets such as dogs and cats, and also other animals such as cows, horses, and goats. Head pressing is usually a sign of a neurological disorder, especially of the forebrain (e.g., [[prosencephalon]] disease),<ref>http://www.petmd.com/dog/conditions/neurological/c_multi_headpressing</ref> or of toxicity due to liver damage, such as [[portosystemic shunt]] and [[hepatic encephalopathy]].<ref name="FaerberDVM1999">{{cite book|author1=Cody W. Faerber|author2=Cody W. Faerber, DVM,S. Mario Durrant, DVM,Jane Fishman Leon, DVM|author3=S. Mario Durrant|title=Canine Medicine and Disease Prevention|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-pU4pfEGqggC&pg=RA1-PA67|date=1 June 1999|publisher=Animal Health Publications|isbn=978-0-9701159-1-1|pages=1}}</ref>
It should be distinguished from [[bunting (animal behavior)|bunting]], which is a normal behavior found in healthy animals.
==Possible causes== * Prosencephalon disease * Liver shunt * [[Brain tumor]] * Metabolic disorder (e.g., [[hyponatremia]] or hyperatremia) * [[Stroke]] * Infection of the nervous system ([[rabies]], parasites, bacterial, viral or fungal infection) * Head trauma<ref>{{cite web|title=Dogs Who Head Press Should See A Vet ASAP. Recognizing This Behavior Could Save Your Dog’s Life.|url=http://www.dogheirs.com/dogheirs/posts/5625-dogs-who-head-press-should-see-a-vet-asap-recognizing-this-behavior-could-save-your-dogs-life#Ft2GmPo32sfaOsbr.99|website=DogHeirs|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref>
===Liver neurotoxicity=== A [[liver shunt]] is a congenital or acquired condition that may lead to toxicity and head pressing. Additional symptoms include drooling and slow maturation early in development. Older animals may suffer from liver cirrhosis.{{citation required|date=February 2017}}
===Viral causes=== Several viruses that cause [[encephalitis]] or [[meningoencephalitis]] can lead to the neurological sign of head pressing, see for example [[Eastern equine encephalitis virus]] and [[Bovine herpesvirus 5]].<ref name="McVeyKennedy2013">{{cite book|author1=D. Scott McVey|author2=Melissa Kennedy|author3=M. M. Chengappa|title=Veterinary Microbiology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KcrUS1gaix0C&pg=PA573|date=10 May 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=1-118-65056-5|pages=573}}</ref><ref name="Gilberd2005">{{cite book|author=Mark Gilberd|title=Natural Remedies For Sheep Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y-ZJs8ufKR0C&pg=PA30|year=2005|publisher=Mark Gilberd|isbn=978-0-9775330-2-2|pages=30}}</ref>
